        {
          "anchor" : "Bars",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Bars",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Bars directly connect one object to another, with the only reaction force being exerted by the bottom surface onto the bar, vertically",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "upwards.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Tension-cables-and-Diagonal-Rods",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Tension cables and Diagonal Rods",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Bars that exert force sideways (eg. into a wall) or tension cables (eg. on a bridge) have one reaction force, exerted by the wall or other connection point onto the support, at a known angle.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Sliding-Attachments",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Sliding Attachments",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A collar on a frictionless rod and a frictionless pin in a slot are both sliding attachments. The only reaction force is perpendicular to the rod or slot.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Hinges",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Hinges",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Hinges are like diagonal rods, however they exert a non-vertical force on the ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "ground",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "emphasis"
            },
            {
              "text" : ". A bar on a rough surface is similar to a",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "hinge. Examples include bridge supports. The two reaction forces are upwards and sideways, exerted by the ground onto the hinge.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Fixed-Supports",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Fixed Supports",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Fixed supports are like hinges, but they cannot rotate. Therefore, we have to consider the moment about the fixed support. The three reaction forces are upwards, sideways, and a moment, exerted by the attachment surface onto the support.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Pulleys",
          "level" : 3,
          "text" : "Pulleys",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Pulleys are the most complex support, since the number of reaction forces depends on the number of cables. Generally, the number of",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "reaction forces is equal to the number of cables supporting the pulley’s weight (eg. “downwards” cables won’t).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
